<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is subnetting?", answer: "Subnetting divides a large IP network into smaller, more manageable sub-networks (subnets). By borrowing bits from the host portion of an IP address to create additional network identifiers, subnetting allows network administrators to create logical divisions, improve security through isolation, reduce broadcast traffic, and use IP addresses more efficiently. Each subnet operates as an independent network segment." },
  { question: "What is CIDR notation?", answer: "CIDR (Classless Inter-Domain Routing) notation represents an IP address and its associated network prefix length, written as IP/prefix. For example, 192.168.1.0/24 means the first 24 bits identify the network and the remaining 8 bits identify hosts. CIDR replaced the older classful addressing system (Class A, B, C) and allows for variable-length subnet masks, enabling much more flexible and efficient allocation of IP addresses." },
  { question: "What is the difference between network and broadcast addresses?", answer: "The network address is the first address in a subnet and identifies the network itself. All host bits are set to 0. The broadcast address is the last address in a subnet and is used to send data to all hosts on that network. All host bits are set to 1. Neither address can be assigned to a host device, which is why the usable host count is always two less than the total address count (except for /31 and /32 subnets)." },
  { question: "What are private IP address ranges?", answer: "Three IP address ranges are reserved for private (internal) networks and cannot be routed on the public internet: 10.0.0.0/8 (10.0.0.0 to 10.255.255.255, over 16 million addresses), 172.16.0.0/12 (172.16.0.0 to 172.31.255.255, about 1 million addresses), and 192.168.0.0/16 (192.168.0.0 to 192.168.255.255, about 65,000 addresses). Organizations use these ranges internally and connect to the internet through NAT (Network Address Translation)." },
  { question: "How do I choose the right subnet size?", answer: "Choose a subnet size based on the number of hosts you need plus room for growth. A /24 subnet provides 254 usable hosts, which works well for most office networks. A /28 provides 14 usable hosts, suitable for small server segments. A /30 provides 2 usable hosts, used for point-to-point links between routers. Always round up to the next power of 2 and account for the network and broadcast addresses. For example, if you need 50 hosts, use a /26 (62 usable hosts), not a /27 (30 usable hosts)." }
]) %>

